{"timestamp": "2026-03-23T23:03:35.675612Z", "stage": "strict_template", "payload": {"intent": "invest_savings", "intents": ["invest_savings"], "response": "Capital Allocation:\n- Full allocation of Rs3,200,000 is covered below.\n- Treat Rs600,000 from the current savings corpus as the emergency reserve; this is part of the existing savings, not extra money.\n- From the remaining Rs2,600,000, keep roughly Rs2,000,000-2,200,000 in safe assets for the house fund.\n- Limit long-term investing to roughly Rs400,000-600,000 from savings until the house timeline and budget are clear.\n- These three buckets together cover the full Rs3,200,000 savings corpus.\n\nMonthly Plan:\n- From monthly surplus, direct about Rs150,000-200,000 to the house fund.\n- Run SIPs of about Rs100,000-150,000 per month into index or hybrid funds for long-term goals.\n- Clarify the target purchase timeline and house budget before increasing equity exposure.\n- Until the house timeline is clear, keep the majority in FD or liquid funds.\n\nStock Suggestions:\n- Use Nifty 50 or Nifty Next 50 index funds as the core equity exposure.\n- Keep direct stocks small: Reliance Industries (energy), TCS / Infosys (IT), HDFC Bank (banking).\n- Limit direct stocks to about 20-30% of the equity bucket, not the full corpus.\n\nWhat Not To Do:\n- Do not invest the entire savings corpus into stocks.\n- Do not rely only on SIPs while leaving existing capital unallocated.\n- Do not increase equity exposure until the goal timeline and budget are clearer."}}
