{"timestamp": "2026-03-23T23:36:27.760168Z", "stage": "strict_template", "payload": {"intent": "multi_goal_planning", "intents": ["multi_goal_planning", "goal_planning", "buy_house"], "response": "Priority:\n- You now have two goals: house first and car second. These need separate buckets and separate timelines.\n\nCapital Allocation:\n- Full allocation of Rs3,200,000 is covered below.\n- Treat Rs600,000 from the current savings corpus as the emergency reserve; this is part of the existing savings, not extra money.\n- Keep roughly Rs1,900,000-2,100,000 in safe assets for the house fund because it is the larger goal.\n- Set aside roughly Rs250,000-350,000 in a separate car fund; keep it in safe assets if the purchase could happen within 1-2 years.\n- Invest only the remaining Rs150,000-450,000 gradually through diversified funds.\n- These buckets together cover the full Rs3,200,000 savings corpus.\n\nInvestment Strategy:\n- Keep the house fund as the priority because it is the larger goal.\n- If the car is needed within 1-2 years, keep the car fund in safe assets.\n- If the car timing is flexible, keep house contributions ahead of the car bucket.\n\nMonthly Plan:\n- Direct about Rs150,000-200,000 per month to the house fund.\n- Direct about Rs50,000 per month to a separate car fund.\n- Run SIPs of about Rs50,000-100,000 per month into index or hybrid funds.\n\nStock Suggestions:\n- Use Nifty 50 or Nifty Next 50 index funds as the core investment exposure.\n- Keep direct stocks small: Reliance Industries (energy), TCS / Infosys (IT), HDFC Bank (banking).\n- Treat direct stocks as only 20-30% of the equity bucket, not the whole portfolio.\n\nWhat Not To Do:\n- Do not mix house money, car money, and long-term investing into one generic pool.\n- Do not let a car purchase consume the house fund without a separate allocation.\n- Do not overreact with aggressive equity while both goal timelines are still unclear."}}
